WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.280
Hi, everybody. Welcome to the Data Science Hangout. If you're joining for the first time,

00:00:12.280 --> 00:00:17.600
it's great to meet you. I'm Rachel, I'm the host of the Data Science Hangout. If this

00:00:17.600 --> 00:00:23.120
is your first Hangout, this is an open space for the whole data science community to connect

00:00:23.120 --> 00:00:28.879
and chat about data science leadership, questions you're facing and really what's going on in

00:00:28.879 --> 00:00:35.639
the world of data science. I'll also say, as I mentioned last time, if you are watching

00:00:35.639 --> 00:00:42.320
this on YouTube in the future, you can also join us live and we'd love to have you. But

00:00:42.320 --> 00:00:46.959
we always want to create spaces where everybody can participate and we can hear from everyone.

00:00:46.959 --> 00:00:54.680
I'm getting a little bit of background, but there's three ways to ask questions. So you

00:00:54.680 --> 00:00:59.560
could jump in live, you can raise your hand on Zoom, you can put questions in the Zoom

00:00:59.560 --> 00:01:04.599
chat and just put a little star next to your question in the Zoom chat if you want me to

00:01:04.599 --> 00:01:10.639
read it out loud. But we also have a Slido link where you can ask questions anonymously

00:01:10.639 --> 00:01:17.959
too. And someone from rstudio will help share that in the chat in just a moment. But I just

00:01:17.959 --> 00:01:22.720
want to reiterate, we love to hear from everyone, no matter your level of experience or area

00:01:22.720 --> 00:01:30.000
of work. So today, I'm so excited to be joined by my co-host, Jenny Listman. Jenny is a Director

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:35.120
of Research at State Space. And Jenny, I'd love to have you introduce yourself. I know

00:01:35.120 --> 00:01:39.360
you've been on here a few weeks before, but share a bit about your work.

00:01:39.360 --> 00:01:48.199
Hi. Well, so first, thanks so much for having me. And thanks to rstudio in general for providing

00:01:48.199 --> 00:01:57.839
this forum for the community. It's great. So I'm Director of Research at State Space

00:01:57.839 --> 00:02:04.519
Labs, and I think probably most people don't know of the company. Some people may know

00:02:04.519 --> 00:02:11.039
of some of our products, but without knowing the name of the company. So it was founded

00:02:11.039 --> 00:02:19.000
by neuroscientists who met at NYU. It was founded about five years ago. So the company

00:02:19.000 --> 00:02:30.199
combines neuroscience, gaming, and AI to build products that help people maximize their performance

00:02:30.199 --> 00:02:36.919
and connect with other people while having fun. So that's vague. But the underlying technology

00:02:36.919 --> 00:02:47.039
is based on research methods from sensory motor neuroscience and cognitive psychology.

00:02:47.039 --> 00:02:53.800
So there are multiple products that the company has. If you're a gamer, in particular, if

00:02:53.800 --> 00:03:00.759
you're an FPS gamer, you might know of our first product, which is called Aim Lab, which

00:03:00.759 --> 00:03:08.600
is a first-person shooter assessment and training scenario, although a lot of people

00:03:08.600 --> 00:03:14.520
use it just because they think it's fun. So they play it as a game on its own. We also

00:03:14.520 --> 00:03:26.619
have Aim Blocks, which is Aim Lab in Roblox. We also have two esports and gaming coaching

00:03:26.619 --> 00:03:36.619
platforms where we can connect players with coaches and training content. And we also

00:03:36.619 --> 00:03:44.259
have a digital health group that's been working for a while in stealth mode. So I think most

00:03:44.259 --> 00:03:50.539
people have no idea, especially people who are familiar with the company through Aim

00:03:50.539 --> 00:03:57.300
Lab or Aim Blocks, they have no idea that we have a digital health arm. So the digital

00:03:57.300 --> 00:04:09.580
health group is working on gamified cognitive and motor performance assessments. And so

00:04:09.580 --> 00:04:22.220
the company, while it's founded, it was founded by scientists and the underlying methods and

00:04:22.220 --> 00:04:28.019
the underlying analytical methods and assessment methods or strategies are developed in-house

00:04:28.019 --> 00:04:36.420
by scientists. Many of the other people who work at the company come from the gaming industry

00:04:36.420 --> 00:04:45.260
or are diehard gamers. So the engineers, the designers, user experience, marketing,

00:04:45.260 --> 00:04:51.619
and analytics, there are people who either came from the gaming industry or are really

00:04:51.619 --> 00:04:59.380
serious gamers. We also have former esports pros and coaches, streamers working at the

00:04:59.380 --> 00:05:08.260
company. So that's state space. I don't know if I think I saw one person nodding when I said

00:05:08.299 --> 00:05:15.899
Aim Lab. So maybe we have some players here. Yeah.

00:05:16.140 --> 00:05:22.339
Yeah. And to maybe put us all in kind of like your frame of reference too, I'm curious, what

00:05:22.339 --> 00:05:27.660
are some of the business problems or things that you're helping to solve or things your team's

00:05:27.660 --> 00:05:28.940
working on too?

00:05:30.380 --> 00:05:46.579
So the company has, I would divide our data questions, problems, goals, into kind of two

00:05:46.579 --> 00:05:55.059
buckets. So first of all, I should preface that by saying a lot of people assume that because

00:05:55.059 --> 00:06:01.940
Aim Lab is free, I think the default assumption is that we're selling people's data, which

00:06:01.940 --> 00:06:11.700
we're not. We just keep all of the data in-house and use it to improve the product or build

00:06:11.700 --> 00:06:21.619
other products. So that's number one. But I would say we have two different buckets of data and

00:06:21.619 --> 00:06:32.100
analysis needs. So one is the kind that you might encounter at a company, another company with a

00:06:32.100 --> 00:06:39.859
customer-facing product. So retention, customer segmentation, marketing analytics, A-B testing. So

00:06:39.859 --> 00:06:47.100
we have those needs. But there's also a lot of science going on at the company. So we have

00:06:47.100 --> 00:06:53.579
another bucket of data needs that might be more what you would expect at a digital health

00:06:53.579 --> 00:07:04.540
company or even in an academic lab. So that even applies to the Aim Lab product or Roblox

00:07:04.540 --> 00:07:12.940
product, so even the gaming products and not just the digital health products. We're still

00:07:12.940 --> 00:07:20.059
doing things like figuring out how do we measure certain aspects of human cognitive

00:07:20.059 --> 00:07:27.179
motor performance through their interactions with a computer? How do we extract scientifically

00:07:27.179 --> 00:07:34.779
valid signals from the data? How do we estimate the extent to which different environmental

00:07:34.779 --> 00:07:43.179
factors or practice habits affect performance? So, yeah, when I think about our data needs,

00:07:43.179 --> 00:07:51.820
I sort of bucket them into these two categories. So we have a data and analytics group that works

00:07:52.540 --> 00:08:02.859
on the problems that you might normally associate with a data science or analytics group. And then

00:08:02.859 --> 00:08:09.500
we have an R&D group or a science team that works on a lot of the other problems, but the

00:08:10.779 --> 00:08:14.779
results of our work feedback into each other.

00:08:17.899 --> 00:08:23.500
That's great. And while we're... I see a few people are very familiar with Aim Lab. I see Sam

00:08:23.500 --> 00:08:28.059
mentioned that. Well, while we're waiting for some of the questions to come in from the audience,

00:08:28.059 --> 00:08:33.900
something I'd love to ask you about from a follow-up previous session was around

00:08:33.900 --> 00:08:41.340
resume reviews. And I know we had brought that up about how it'd be great to be able to connect

00:08:41.340 --> 00:08:46.940
people from the community, people that could share their resume and others that could help provide

00:08:46.940 --> 00:08:54.619
feedback. And I'm curious if there is specific feedback or tips that you generally share with

00:08:54.619 --> 00:09:08.219
people? Good question. I think... So first of all, I think a theme that I've seen on this,

00:09:09.739 --> 00:09:15.900
the data science hangout, but just in general online among the data science community is like,

00:09:15.900 --> 00:09:22.460
well, how do I transition? How do I get my first job in data science? And I think part of the

00:09:23.260 --> 00:09:32.460
problem is just the word data scientist. It means so many different things that at a certain point,

00:09:32.460 --> 00:09:44.219
it loses meaning, right? I think people use that term to describe a business analyst or

00:09:45.739 --> 00:09:50.219
someone in another context, someone could just use the same term to describe

00:09:50.780 --> 00:09:57.820
someone who's using neural nets to solve problems. Right now, I don't do either of those things.

00:09:58.859 --> 00:10:07.500
So I think partly the data science community might need to start doing a better job at

00:10:09.900 --> 00:10:13.900
describing these different kinds of jobs, because if you're just starting out

00:10:14.859 --> 00:10:21.099
or you're trying to, whether you're transitioning out of academia or you're an undergrad or

00:10:21.099 --> 00:10:27.179
graduating with a master's degree and you want to go into data science, what does that even mean?

00:10:27.179 --> 00:10:34.859
So I think it might be good if the community could come up with some better definitions. I

00:10:34.859 --> 00:10:41.020
know there are some people who have done some really good work around that. And

00:10:41.179 --> 00:10:47.179
as far as general advice, I would say one of the things that I've seen

00:10:49.979 --> 00:10:57.419
are people who are not, this is what we talked about previously, people who are not good at

00:10:59.580 --> 00:11:09.099
promoting themselves. And I, in a previous life, was definitely guilty of that. And so I think

00:11:09.659 --> 00:11:18.539
just that skill alone, learning how to write about your own accomplishments as if it was someone

00:11:18.539 --> 00:11:24.460
else writing for you, is a skill to learn on its own. Yeah.

00:11:25.820 --> 00:11:30.539
Yeah, I think that was something Libby had mentioned before in the chat too,

00:11:30.539 --> 00:11:35.419
like thinking about somebody else writing that about you. It's good to hear that.

00:11:35.500 --> 00:11:42.460
It's good feedback. I will mention too that this is just an experiment, but I was thinking if we

00:11:42.460 --> 00:11:50.619
wanted to start a resume review club through the Data Science Hangout, I did make a Google form

00:11:50.619 --> 00:11:56.700
where you could just say, you could upload your resume or you could raise your hand to say,

00:11:57.260 --> 00:12:02.780
I would love to help review someone else's. So I just put that link in the chat if people want

00:12:02.780 --> 00:12:09.659
to check it out. Yeah, I would say this is totally my fault. I did this to myself.

00:12:11.580 --> 00:12:18.539
This came up because, I don't know how long ago it was, maybe three, four weeks ago,

00:12:19.580 --> 00:12:26.380
someone at State Space forwarded me a resume for someone who was applying for one of our

00:12:26.380 --> 00:12:34.460
data analyst positions and asking, is this person qualified? Should I tell them to apply?

00:12:36.219 --> 00:12:44.539
So I looked at the resume and immediately certain things jumped out at me like the

00:12:45.820 --> 00:12:51.580
most important accomplishment within each job, that previous job that had been posted,

00:12:52.299 --> 00:12:57.419
the most important accomplishment at that job was listed last in the bullet points.

00:12:59.659 --> 00:13:06.700
For more than one job that was listed, this person was, before giving themselves credit

00:13:06.700 --> 00:13:14.859
for anything, was referring to their colleagues, which is wonderful. I trained under this person

00:13:14.859 --> 00:13:20.140
who helped me or I contributed to something, something, something, but then they had done

00:13:20.140 --> 00:13:25.340
things on their own and they weren't promoting that stuff first. And then out of curiosity,

00:13:25.340 --> 00:13:30.380
I looked at this person's LinkedIn page and saw, well, there's a whole bunch of amazing things that

00:13:30.380 --> 00:13:37.659
were listed on their LinkedIn page that hadn't even made it onto their resume. So I responded

00:13:37.659 --> 00:13:44.059
and said, they may very well be qualified to apply for this job, but before that happens,

00:13:44.059 --> 00:13:52.619
forget about this job. This person just needs to really redo their resume and do a better job at

00:13:52.619 --> 00:14:04.380
telling everyone how wonderful they are. And then after I saw that, I messaged the New York

00:14:05.340 --> 00:14:14.940
Slack chapter for the New York Our Ladies Slack group asking, does anyone know of a forum where

00:14:14.940 --> 00:14:24.539
people can get their resume reviewed? And there wasn't really a response. And then I mentioned it

00:14:24.539 --> 00:14:30.539
on a data science hangout and realized, oh, I just assigned that to myself probably.

00:14:31.500 --> 00:14:39.260
So, but yeah, no, thank you, Rachel, for kicking that off because I can't do it by myself. I think

00:14:39.260 --> 00:14:48.140
that's part of the point. Yeah. Thank you for the idea of it. And we had a few people use it already,

00:14:48.140 --> 00:14:55.979
even just as an experiment and got great feedback on how the process worked. I'm sure we'll have

00:14:55.979 --> 00:15:03.179
more people starting to use it. So I'll keep in touch with you of how that's going. I see, Ethan,

00:15:03.179 --> 00:15:10.299
you just put a question into the chat if you want to just jump in. Yeah. Hi, Jenny. I'm an M Lab

00:15:10.299 --> 00:15:18.219
fan, FPS junkie. So when I see that there's an M Lab company, I'm so excited that you'll be talking

00:15:18.219 --> 00:15:24.059
about. So you mentioned that M Lab was started by neuroscientists. I'm curious how the task,

00:15:24.619 --> 00:15:30.859
basically, for everyone here, M Labs, basically, you have different tasks that you, basically,

00:15:30.859 --> 00:15:37.260
sensory tasks that you click on. And how was the task first designed? Was it driven by

00:15:37.900 --> 00:15:46.460
the neurological science side or the gaming side? And also, could you give us a flavor of what

00:15:46.460 --> 00:15:53.739
sorts of analysis you can do on M Lab data? Basically, I'm trying to imagine, could gamers

00:15:53.739 --> 00:16:07.419
actually help healthcare research? Yeah. So they can. So the first tasks and the underlying

00:16:07.419 --> 00:16:21.179
technology was developed based on the kinds of experiments that often go on in psych labs,

00:16:22.619 --> 00:16:32.859
except with a much more boring stimulus. Like there's a horizontal line on the screen,

00:16:32.859 --> 00:16:38.940
and there's a vertical line on the screen, and click when you see this. So

00:16:41.580 --> 00:16:50.380
some of those basic types of experiments were, basically, overlaid with gaming scenarios.

00:16:52.059 --> 00:16:59.659
So, well, I see someone in the chat, not just executive function tasks, but there are,

00:16:59.659 --> 00:17:03.820
I don't know, maybe at least like 100 tasks right now in M Lab. Some of them

00:17:03.820 --> 00:17:10.380
concentrate more on tracking something that's moving, like a smooth tracking movement. Some

00:17:10.380 --> 00:17:20.859
of them are more ballistic movements. Some of them assess working memory. But the trick with

00:17:20.859 --> 00:17:26.060
something like M Lab is that, like I said, a typical experiment in a lab,

00:17:26.859 --> 00:17:34.859
you know, people are paid. They're there for, you know, maybe an hour, and it's boring,

00:17:35.420 --> 00:17:45.500
but they're being paid. So if it's a game, it has to be fun, right? So the tasks in M Lab have to

00:17:45.500 --> 00:17:54.939
balance the, you know, from the perspective of the scientist, being able to collect scientifically

00:17:55.500 --> 00:18:05.819
useful data, while being fun enough that people want to play it, and also being similar enough

00:18:05.819 --> 00:18:12.619
to the gaming scenarios that they're actually trying to train for. So it's a total balance.

00:18:12.619 --> 00:18:19.339
It's a continuous balance when, you know, for any of the tasks that are designed.

00:18:20.300 --> 00:18:27.180
Yes, I saw you share an article in the Washington Post about people actually asked you guys to,

00:18:27.180 --> 00:18:31.500
can you make the game more laggy, just to make it more similar to the actual game,

00:18:32.380 --> 00:18:37.180
the tournament they have to compete in. I think the article mentioned that PUBG gamers,

00:18:37.180 --> 00:18:42.140
that they asked you guys, can you lower the FPS so that it's similar to the actual tournament

00:18:42.140 --> 00:18:48.859
that they're in. Yeah, I mean, people can, you know, change their settings in the game to,

00:18:48.859 --> 00:18:54.859
you know, simulate whatever they're using in their favorite game. But we have,

00:18:55.819 --> 00:19:06.939
a couple of times, we have asked M Lab users to participate in research projects. So we have had,

00:19:06.939 --> 00:19:12.939
you know, research projects that were done directly with, you know, small numbers of M Lab

00:19:12.939 --> 00:19:18.459
users. But for the most part, people are just playing the game, however they want to play the

00:19:18.459 --> 00:19:23.979
game, with whatever equipment they want to use. Typically, you know, they're just playing the

00:19:24.380 --> 00:19:28.540
typically in their home, it could be two in the morning, it could be one in the afternoon,

00:19:29.180 --> 00:19:33.420
you know, somebody might play it for 10 minutes, somebody might play it every day.

00:19:35.660 --> 00:19:40.780
And, you know, that's just so, so those are not experiments exactly, right? It's just whatever

00:19:40.780 --> 00:19:49.979
data is coming in. We also, like I said, we now have this digital health group. So we are using

00:19:49.979 --> 00:19:56.219
tasks, we're sort of taking the tasks from M Lab, and in some cases, porting them to

00:19:57.579 --> 00:20:05.979
tablet, in some cases, leaving them as a, you know, PC based tasks. We were working with several

00:20:05.979 --> 00:20:12.859
different universities on projects, having to do with assessing concussion, assessing

00:20:13.819 --> 00:20:24.060
cognitive changes under hypoxia, so low levels of oxygen, oxygen deprivation that you might

00:20:24.060 --> 00:20:32.219
experience at high altitude. We have another research project with pediatric cerebral palsy

00:20:32.219 --> 00:20:44.540
patients. So the same technology that's and gamify tasks that are that were built for M Lab

00:20:45.819 --> 00:20:53.260
can be used for for these research purposes and to, you know, assess cognitive and motor

00:20:53.260 --> 00:21:01.099
performance outside of gaming. Yeah, I guess like, on the side of gamification, it's not just

00:21:01.660 --> 00:21:07.739
making it like a game, you also have the review part. So after every session on M Lab, if you know,

00:21:08.540 --> 00:21:12.699
it's actually tell you what you're good at, and you're tracking your performance over time.

00:21:13.260 --> 00:21:17.979
So it's telling you something that you may have a lower left side screen weaknesses,

00:21:17.979 --> 00:21:22.380
and maybe you're slow on that area, which is quite interesting. The other side is that you

00:21:22.380 --> 00:21:30.459
have a leaderboard, so people can publish their results. Yeah, right. So people use it as a,

00:21:30.459 --> 00:21:35.979
you know, to warm up before they play for their favorite game, or as a trainer to improve in their

00:21:35.979 --> 00:21:42.219
favorite game. But like I mentioned before, there are plenty of people who just, you know, enjoy

00:21:42.219 --> 00:21:49.500
playing in M Lab as it is and compete for positions on the leaderboard. Yeah.

00:21:51.260 --> 00:21:57.739
Thanks, Jenny. That's interesting to think about all the data behind the games. And I mean,

00:21:57.739 --> 00:22:02.859
I know Wordle is one that's been top of mind for a lot of people lately,

00:22:02.859 --> 00:22:10.780
but thinking like what data could be behind that too. I see there was an anonymous question that

00:22:10.780 --> 00:22:16.300
came in that was what are some things or skills specific to research that aren't traditionally

00:22:16.300 --> 00:22:23.979
part of a data science exclusive role? I mean, what are some of the skills that

00:22:24.859 --> 00:22:29.579
are specific to the, I assume this person is asking what are some of the skills that are

00:22:29.579 --> 00:22:37.739
specific to like the R&D team versus the data science team? I think so, yeah. Okay. So for

00:22:37.739 --> 00:22:48.859
one, some of the roles on the R&D team really require domain expertise. So some of the people

00:22:48.939 --> 00:22:55.020
on the R&D team have PhDs in neuroscience, cognitive psychology,

00:22:58.060 --> 00:23:04.140
bioengineering, but specifically, you know, people have worked on brain computer interface

00:23:04.140 --> 00:23:11.260
projects. So people who have experience analyzing very specific types of data

00:23:12.140 --> 00:23:19.339
and who have a background in cognitive neuroscience, cognitive psychology,

00:23:20.699 --> 00:23:29.500
which, you know, isn't necessary for some of the other data science or analytics roles at the

00:23:29.500 --> 00:23:38.300
company. Speaking of roles at the company, I know that you are hiring for a bunch of different

00:23:38.380 --> 00:23:44.859
roles. Right. And curious to hear what you're looking for in each of those roles and

00:23:45.660 --> 00:23:54.060
if they're on your team or. Yeah. So I am not a hiring manager for any of the current roles. We

00:23:54.060 --> 00:24:02.939
don't have a role currently. Right now I'm on the R&D team. So the data and analytics team has,

00:24:02.939 --> 00:24:13.500
I believe, two openings right now. Yes, Aaliyah, this is one of my co-workers, is on the call. So

00:24:14.060 --> 00:24:24.780
there's data scientist roles on the analytics team. And there's also a marketing analytics

00:24:24.780 --> 00:24:30.219
position, which I believe is separate from the data scientist roles. There's also

00:24:30.300 --> 00:24:40.780
in digital health, there's a role in the digital health team that would be more along the lines of

00:24:40.780 --> 00:24:50.219
a biostatistician. So those are the current open, you know, data related roles. But I should mention

00:24:50.219 --> 00:25:00.140
that there's plenty of open roles. There's plenty of openings in engineering. There's plenty of

00:25:00.380 --> 00:25:07.819
marketing product. So if you have, you know, friends who might be interested, definitely

00:25:08.540 --> 00:25:14.380
direct them to our, I think all of the jobs are listed on on Lever, but I'm sure if you just

00:25:14.380 --> 00:25:20.540
Google it, people would find all of the open positions. Awesome. And Aaliyah, feel free to

00:25:20.540 --> 00:25:24.859
share them in the chat too, if you want to share the links to the job postings.

00:25:25.020 --> 00:25:30.140
But just a reminder, everyone, feel free to just raise your hand on Zoom if you want to just jump

00:25:30.140 --> 00:25:38.459
in live as well. But one question, Jenny, I'd love to ask you, and we actually used to ask this at

00:25:38.459 --> 00:25:44.540
the beginning of all the data science Hangouts, but it's, what are you most excited about right

00:25:44.540 --> 00:25:52.219
now, in data science for the next year? Or projects at work that are most exciting to you?

00:25:52.380 --> 00:26:02.619
So for me, at the current projects that we're working on, I think, you know, Statespace is a

00:26:02.619 --> 00:26:18.540
young company. So we're at the point now where I, we are better able to take advantage of all the

00:26:19.180 --> 00:26:28.699
data that that we're collecting. So, you know, we have this enormous volume of performance data,

00:26:28.699 --> 00:26:38.219
of human performance data. We've been able to write a couple of journal articles based on that.

00:26:38.219 --> 00:26:46.540
So if you're, if you're coming from academia, the size of our data sets,

00:26:46.619 --> 00:26:53.500
is really exciting. So, so that, you know, sort of like a playground, if you're, if you're coming

00:26:53.500 --> 00:27:00.140
out of academia to have access to such a large amount of data. So on a regular basis, I find

00:27:00.140 --> 00:27:11.500
that exciting. But we're at a point now where we are going to be able to, you know, combine data

00:27:11.819 --> 00:27:18.140
from the different products that we have, so that they can feed off of each other, to really

00:27:18.939 --> 00:27:30.859
maximize the experience of our users, and get better at personalizing the user's experience

00:27:31.420 --> 00:27:39.180
to help them improve. So I think that, you know, it's been like a long time coming.

00:27:39.579 --> 00:27:44.540
And, you know, before you can do something like that, you actually have to just spend a lot of

00:27:44.540 --> 00:27:52.780
time immersing yourself in the data, to even figure out what's there. So yeah, so that,

00:27:52.780 --> 00:27:54.540
that's on the horizon.

00:27:57.579 --> 00:28:03.500
Thank you. I know, just from LinkedIn, and I spend a lot of time on LinkedIn, but,

00:28:03.739 --> 00:28:09.260
but you had previously had your own consulting company as well. And I know there's a lot of

00:28:09.260 --> 00:28:15.819
people in the data science space, who maybe even during COVID, just recently started consulting

00:28:15.819 --> 00:28:22.219
businesses. And I'd love to hear a bit about your experience in that. And if you have some tips that

00:28:22.219 --> 00:28:33.420
you might share with people listening. Yeah, so I, my, my, my, my, my, my, my, my, my, my,

00:28:33.420 --> 00:28:40.699
my initial academic training was in anthropological genomics. I worked in a

00:28:40.699 --> 00:28:52.060
psychiatric genetics lab for a number of years. And then when I left academia, the role that I had

00:28:52.060 --> 00:29:03.339
was in a, a center for STEM education at NYU's engineering school. And I did some,

00:29:05.739 --> 00:29:11.099
you know, project outcome measures, I instituted a lot of,

00:29:13.739 --> 00:29:18.619
a lot of quantification of the programs that they were offering to, you know, they,

00:29:18.619 --> 00:29:25.500
they offered programs to like thousands of local kids in middle school and high school,

00:29:26.060 --> 00:29:33.099
but weren't necessarily keeping track of the effects that the programs had. So I was able to,

00:29:34.859 --> 00:29:39.260
to institute that, write some papers on that. I wrote a lot of grants

00:29:39.979 --> 00:29:53.339
in that role. And a specific problem came up that I thought I can solve, I can probably solve this

00:29:53.339 --> 00:29:59.339
with R. And it had been a couple of years since I had had to use R. I think I started using R

00:29:59.339 --> 00:30:04.300
in grad school, probably like 2004. So there was no R studio, it was all command line.

00:30:04.699 --> 00:30:10.540
But I thought I, I, there's this problem and I'm pretty sure I can, you know, find a package and

00:30:10.540 --> 00:30:18.140
solve it in R. And when I started doing that, I was like, you know, I miss this. I miss this part.

00:30:18.140 --> 00:30:26.300
Like I, I loved my job. I loved the people I worked with. But I realized like I, I, I need to,

00:30:26.300 --> 00:30:33.020
I need to do this again. So I left that job and set aside a chunk of time

00:30:33.579 --> 00:30:43.579
to turn myself into a data science consultant. And to do that, I, and I, I know this is advice

00:30:43.579 --> 00:30:48.380
given, you know, maybe controversial advice given to people like, oh, assign yourself projects and

00:30:48.380 --> 00:30:54.219
make a blog. And so, which I did. And I, I do understand that in order to be able to do that,

00:30:54.219 --> 00:31:01.099
you have to have enough free time to, to be able to accomplish that, which I did.

00:31:03.500 --> 00:31:11.420
And, you know, basically assign myself problems that would force me to have to learn new packages,

00:31:11.420 --> 00:31:20.939
new tools, new analytical methods. And after doing that, I, I landed a, a gig as a

00:31:21.739 --> 00:31:28.380
consultant for an education nonprofit that had a gigantic longitudinal data set.

00:31:30.380 --> 00:31:38.140
And I worked for them for about maybe like a year and a half before starting

00:31:40.859 --> 00:31:44.619
at Statespace. And even for Statespace, I, at first I was a consultant

00:31:45.579 --> 00:31:52.780
writing a really large grant, like a monster grant. Didn't get funded, but that's okay because

00:31:52.780 --> 00:31:58.780
it laid, it laid groundwork for a lot of other stuff. And then, and then I was, I was hired

00:31:59.579 --> 00:32:09.819
full-time at Statespace. But yeah, so that I was not, you know, a full-time employee for this

00:32:10.219 --> 00:32:14.219
company, the, I mean, for the, for the nonprofit, the education nonprofit,

00:32:14.219 --> 00:32:19.579
but it took up enough of my time that it was, you know, for me, basically a full-time job.

00:32:21.739 --> 00:32:28.459
What was that transition like of being a consultant for a company and then coming on full-time?

00:32:29.339 --> 00:32:40.140
So Statespace is unusual. It's, the culture is unusual. The, you know, the flexibility of the

00:32:40.140 --> 00:32:48.380
work hours is unusual. So I, it may, like the transition for me might not be what other people

00:32:49.260 --> 00:33:00.219
would experience. The company has been remote from the beginning. There was no real office

00:33:00.219 --> 00:33:07.819
when the company was really small. And then people started getting hired who were in different time

00:33:07.819 --> 00:33:15.579
zones. There were thoughts of getting an office, but then the pandemic hit. So, and in the meantime,

00:33:15.579 --> 00:33:21.660
the company raised more money and expanded. There are people who work at, for Statespace,

00:33:22.219 --> 00:33:29.260
you know, all over the world. You know, we manage, you know, in a single meeting,

00:33:29.260 --> 00:33:37.819
there could be people on like seven different time zones. Right. So, and the, the culture at

00:33:37.819 --> 00:33:48.380
Statespace is people just have to get their work done. So nobody's really a nine to five employee

00:33:48.380 --> 00:33:59.180
at Statespace. And I, I understand that, that, that also some people have negative opinions

00:33:59.180 --> 00:34:03.900
about a company that's run that way, where, you know, the work hours are like, just get your work

00:34:03.900 --> 00:34:09.100
done. It's whatever the hours are that, that you need to do it. And, you know, there's no specific

00:34:09.100 --> 00:34:17.659
vacation time, just take vacation when you need it. And I understand that there are circumstances

00:34:17.659 --> 00:34:22.780
in which a company might take advantage of that, or where people might work for a company that has

00:34:22.780 --> 00:34:31.979
that kind of policy where they would feel really pressured to just never take vacation. And, and

00:34:31.979 --> 00:34:41.340
it's just, that's just not how it works at Statespace. So I think I've had, there's one

00:34:41.340 --> 00:34:50.219
job that I had when I left academia. I think I was there for maybe a year. Not, not the, not the job

00:34:50.219 --> 00:34:56.780
at NYU. It was a different job where it was really nine to five. And I remember the first time I had

00:34:56.860 --> 00:35:04.139
to, I had a dentist appointment, I had just a dental cleaning, and I had to take a half of a,

00:35:04.139 --> 00:35:12.139
of a sick day to get my teeth cleaned. And I was just like, I don't, I don't think I can deal with

00:35:12.139 --> 00:35:17.020
this. And, and I, I totally understand this is just a personal preference. There are plenty of people

00:35:17.020 --> 00:35:23.419
who want a job where they know at, you know, 5 p.m. or 6 p.m. I'm done. Nobody can bother me.

00:35:23.419 --> 00:35:31.899
And when it's the weekend, it's my weekend and no one can bother me. For me and my family,

00:35:31.899 --> 00:35:39.580
this, the level of flexibility that I have at Statespace is actually really important and,

00:35:40.939 --> 00:35:48.540
you know, a huge benefit for me. So as far as like the hours and, you know, there wasn't,

00:35:48.540 --> 00:35:53.659
for me, it didn't feel like such a big transition going from consulting to working full-time at

00:35:53.659 --> 00:36:03.500
Statespace. Other than, you know, I just, I, I now have like a lot more colleagues and,

00:36:05.020 --> 00:36:10.300
you know, work, definitely work more hours. Yeah. Yeah. It sounds like there is an awesome

00:36:10.300 --> 00:36:15.899
culture at Statespace just from even previous conversations that we had as well. And I see,

00:36:15.979 --> 00:36:19.580
Sam, you actually just asked a question about this as well. Do you want to jump in?

00:36:22.459 --> 00:36:26.699
Or I can, I can read it and you can add context, but it's, how do you ensure

00:36:26.699 --> 00:36:34.699
employees at Statespace have a work-life balance to avoid burnout? That's a good question. I mean,

00:36:34.699 --> 00:36:41.580
it is definitely a risk. So managers have to be really careful and be on top of that

00:36:42.300 --> 00:36:48.379
to make sure that that doesn't happen. I think it depends on the role that somebody has at the

00:36:48.379 --> 00:36:57.179
company and the level of, of responsibility that they have. For some of the people in,

00:36:57.179 --> 00:37:00.780
for example, engineering, or we have a really, really large community team,

00:37:01.659 --> 00:37:09.979
meaning the people who are on Discord or Twitter communicating, you know, in constant communication

00:37:09.979 --> 00:37:18.459
with users responding in real time when people have a question or have a problem. And so for

00:37:18.459 --> 00:37:26.620
those people, you know, certainly there's work to do on the weekends, or if something crashes,

00:37:27.260 --> 00:37:35.179
there have to be engineers who are willing to, to fix something on the weekends. But yeah,

00:37:35.179 --> 00:37:42.139
managers just have to be really careful about who has to take responsibility for that kind of thing,

00:37:42.139 --> 00:37:50.139
like in an emergency. Yeah. Yeah. Thank you. And thanks, Sam, for asking that question as well,

00:37:50.139 --> 00:37:55.659
because I think that's something that a lot of us, I mean, I know there's a lot of talk around

00:37:55.659 --> 00:38:02.379
burnout, but how do people know when they're actually experiencing burnout before it's too late?

00:38:02.939 --> 00:38:12.219
Yeah. And again, I think that that is an issue that people have with companies that have this

00:38:12.219 --> 00:38:23.340
sort of, you know, nebulous working hours and lack of specific vacation time. All I can say is,

00:38:23.340 --> 00:38:28.860
I think it's working pretty well at State Space. You know, personally, I haven't had a problem with

00:38:29.739 --> 00:38:38.540
it, you know, up to now. I mean, I appreciate being able to, you know, in the middle of the

00:38:38.540 --> 00:38:48.139
week, if I have to take two hours during business hours to make phone calls to manage my 87-year-old

00:38:48.139 --> 00:38:55.260
mother's health care, I can do that. I can, if it's, you know, a family member's birthday,

00:38:55.739 --> 00:39:00.860
I can stop working at three and make a cake from scratch and do whatever I want to do to

00:39:00.860 --> 00:39:10.379
help them celebrate their birthday. And then I don't feel, for me personally, then I get work

00:39:10.379 --> 00:39:15.580
done on the weekend because it's really quiet and I don't have any meetings. I don't have any work

00:39:15.580 --> 00:39:24.860
related meetings. And it doesn't bother me that I'm doing that because I also know that, you know,

00:39:24.860 --> 00:39:29.979
I have the freedom in the middle of the week to exercise or, you know, do these other things I

00:39:29.979 --> 00:39:36.860
need to do. But it's definitely a personal preference. There are people who really need

00:39:37.899 --> 00:39:45.100
specific work hours for their lifestyle. I'm curious from the group here as well,

00:39:45.100 --> 00:39:49.820
like if you have other tips too for avoiding burnout, or if there's things people want to

00:39:49.820 --> 00:39:57.100
share in the chat. I see, Zach, you put a question in the chat if you want to jump in.

00:39:57.100 --> 00:40:04.060
Yeah, I was just, of course, I'm British, UK law is a lot different to US law, especially around

00:40:04.060 --> 00:40:09.899
holiday, and to take time off. I was wondering, how do you make sure, again, it's the burnout

00:40:09.899 --> 00:40:18.219
question, is there a minimum days off, even because you said there's not like unlimited,

00:40:18.219 --> 00:40:23.179
you can take as much days off? How do you ensure, other than just a general culture thing that

00:40:23.179 --> 00:40:28.459
actually people do take enough days off? Because otherwise, there will be burnout no matter how

00:40:28.459 --> 00:40:37.659
much they love their work. So HR does keep tabs on that. And they will make people take time off.

00:40:37.659 --> 00:40:45.260
Like, I mean, they can see who's not taking time off. So yeah, occasionally people are

00:40:45.979 --> 00:40:51.179
just told, like, go disappear for a while. You need to do that. Yeah.

00:40:53.580 --> 00:41:00.620
I know we had to do that at our studio, because we do have unlimited time off. But sometimes when

00:41:00.620 --> 00:41:07.100
you have unlimited, you don't actually take it off. So we have like quarterly check-ins now,

00:41:07.100 --> 00:41:11.260
where you have to say, like, are you on track to take this minimum amount?

00:41:12.060 --> 00:41:17.260
Yeah, that's really, yeah, that's really good. I guess it's also the pandemic, you're not going

00:41:17.260 --> 00:41:23.260
on holiday, or people are starting now. I know for me, I've not taken enough days off. And

00:41:23.979 --> 00:41:29.979
right for mine, they reset end of March. So they just reset, I always have to, I've only worked a

00:41:29.979 --> 00:41:33.979
couple years, but I always get told in March, I have to take like four, five, six days off

00:41:33.979 --> 00:41:38.459
to make sure I hit minimum requirements. Yeah, people don't even know what day of the week it

00:41:38.459 --> 00:41:47.100
is anymore. So that definitely made it made it more difficult. Yeah. I like Mark's tips in the

