deleting LinkedIn, and then Monday, I'll let myself put it back on my phone.

00:42:22.300 --> 00:42:29.979
So we'll see how that works. Yeah, I mean, I think for some people, like any other phone app, these

00:42:30.379 --> 00:42:36.459
work related phone apps, people are just sort of addicted to clicking on them.

00:42:37.899 --> 00:42:44.540
So yeah, definitely. I see there was a another anonymous question earlier that was any insight

00:42:44.540 --> 00:42:51.580
on how trends like 5g and AR VR would shape the technology investment with AIM Labs?

00:42:52.139 --> 00:43:03.260
So, I mean, VR, you know, I think any company that's working on anything related to video games,

00:43:03.260 --> 00:43:12.540
you know, has to be paying attention to VR. We have released a couple of AIM Lab tasks on VR.

00:43:13.500 --> 00:43:22.939
So, you know, any company that is working on anything that's presented in the form of a video

00:43:22.939 --> 00:43:33.179
game, whether it's for entertainment or for health care, has to be looking at multiple

00:43:33.979 --> 00:43:43.580
multiple platforms, PC, console, mobile, tablet, VR. Yeah.

00:43:45.820 --> 00:43:54.139
How have you seen the customer experience or from the data based on people are using VR or not?

00:43:55.020 --> 00:44:00.860
Well, so we, like I said, we've only released a couple of tasks in VR mode,

00:44:01.340 --> 00:44:09.659
I assume, you know, sort of as a test to just to test out that technology. They seem to be pretty

00:44:09.659 --> 00:44:17.500
well received. I mean, there's, you know, I think the headset technology still has a ways to go in

00:44:17.500 --> 00:44:25.500
terms of not everyone is physically comfortable with headsets. You know, there are people who

00:44:25.500 --> 00:44:32.540
get nauseous from them, things like that. And there's also it's an additional cost, right? Like

00:44:32.540 --> 00:44:39.340
if you're trying to reach a large number of people, you know, mobile phones are probably

00:44:39.340 --> 00:44:45.020
the easiest way to reach the largest number of people without assuming that everybody's going

00:44:45.020 --> 00:44:52.620
to go out and buy another piece of equipment. So right now, headsets are pretty expensive,

00:44:52.620 --> 00:44:55.340
and it's not like most people have it in their home.

00:44:58.540 --> 00:45:03.739
When you were talking about some of the work that state space is doing in public health,

00:45:04.540 --> 00:45:12.139
do you have partnerships with different hospitals or organizations? Or what does that look like?

00:45:12.699 --> 00:45:22.300
So right now, we have several research projects that are that are ongoing. One with Mount Sinai

00:45:22.379 --> 00:45:31.020
Hospital in New York. That's the project that we're doing where pediatric patients with cerebral

00:45:31.020 --> 00:45:39.500
palsy are using some aim lab tasks that have been adapted for, you know, some are on tablets,

00:45:39.500 --> 00:45:46.540
some are on PC, but adapted for use in that context. And for that, it's not only

00:45:47.020 --> 00:45:56.939
that the mechanics of the tasks had to be changed, but all of the imagery and sounds and text had to

00:45:56.939 --> 00:46:04.540
be changed because there can't be any gun imagery or, you know, anything about shooting like this

00:46:04.540 --> 00:46:11.419
is a tool that's being used in a hospital and with kids. So the design team had to totally overhaul

00:46:12.139 --> 00:46:19.340
the tasks and, you know, turn, like remove anything having to do with a gun or words having

00:46:19.340 --> 00:46:26.699
to do with kill or shooting. One of the tasks, it's a tracking task. And this is like one of

00:46:26.699 --> 00:46:37.260
my favorite things that came out of our work over the past year. It's a tracking task. So,

00:46:37.260 --> 00:46:41.899
you know, someone has to follow something that's moving on the screen and track it.

00:46:42.860 --> 00:46:51.580
And so instead of targets like round shaped targets, the targets are cats.

00:46:52.379 --> 00:46:57.979
And they, I don't know, for people who are familiar with video games,

00:46:58.699 --> 00:47:05.580
the target's health or an opponent's health is, you know, sometimes shown on the screen

00:47:05.580 --> 00:47:11.500
as like a decrease, a bar that's decreasing in size or like, you know, something that's colored

00:47:11.500 --> 00:47:20.139
that's fading. So the cat's health is like a rainbow that's basically coming out of the cat's

00:47:20.139 --> 00:47:31.260
butt. And it just like shortens as the cat's life shortens. So yeah, so we had to adapt the tasks

00:47:31.419 --> 00:47:40.219
for use for pediatric patients. And definitely our design team had a lot of fun with that one.

00:47:40.939 --> 00:47:49.179
And then we have partnerships at Indiana University where we have a large study going

00:47:49.179 --> 00:47:58.939
on with a lot of the athletes at Indiana University assessing concussion using adapted in-lab tasks.

00:47:58.939 --> 00:48:05.659
And that's also at Indiana University is where we're doing a study on hypoxia.

00:48:08.620 --> 00:48:20.780
Yeah. And we've also partnered with companies that wanted to use in-lab tasks to assess

00:48:21.500 --> 00:48:32.139
their products or to, you know, to test out their products. So we've done some efficacy testing

00:48:33.419 --> 00:48:43.979
or we've used in-lab task metrics as outcome metrics for efficacy testing of nutritional

00:48:43.979 --> 00:48:58.219
supplements in partnership with a CRO. And we've built tasks for Kernel, which is a

00:48:58.219 --> 00:49:07.500
neuroscience-based company. So yeah, we're using in-lab tasks for other kinds of research.

00:49:08.379 --> 00:49:13.419
Cool. Thank you. I see, Raphael, you just put something, a question into the chat.

00:49:13.419 --> 00:49:14.699
Would you want to ask that one live?

00:49:19.899 --> 00:49:27.820
Yeah, I see this question about, you've read an article saying that cognitive abilities

00:49:27.820 --> 00:49:35.979
begin to decline at 26. And we rely on previous experience more at that age. So is this true?

00:49:36.860 --> 00:49:42.620
And does it mean I have to try harder to beat my 12-year-old brother? So that's a good question.

00:49:43.820 --> 00:49:55.820
We did collect some data on age and performance in AIM Lab. And our data did indicate that

00:49:56.540 --> 00:50:08.060
performance seems to peak before 26, like 24, 25 years old. But I would qualify that by saying

00:50:08.060 --> 00:50:14.939
that, you know, the data that we're collecting, our data set is messy. This is not under controlled

00:50:14.939 --> 00:50:21.820
conditions, right? Our users are playing AIM Lab at home. All of their equipment is different.

00:50:22.139 --> 00:50:28.300
And we have no idea what time of day they're playing, right? We don't collect information

00:50:28.300 --> 00:50:36.060
on their gender. So it's not like this was done in a lab, but our data showed that there was a

00:50:36.060 --> 00:50:46.540
decline after like mid-20s. And there have been published studies that were conducted under,

00:50:46.540 --> 00:50:54.139
with data conducted under controlled conditions that have similar results, like at around that age.

00:50:54.860 --> 00:51:05.979
Yeah. But yeah, you know, things like game sense and experience, you know, cognitive control in

00:51:05.979 --> 00:51:14.219
terms of restraining yourself so you don't shoot a teammate instead of an enemy, things like that.

00:51:14.540 --> 00:51:17.340
You know, age might give you an advantage.

00:51:21.820 --> 00:51:28.379
Thanks, Jenny. I see Raphael saying, oh no. I was thinking the same. Jordan, I see you have

00:51:28.379 --> 00:51:34.780
your hand raised. Do you want to jump in? Yeah, sure. So specifically on that last question. So

00:51:34.780 --> 00:51:39.659
I work at a company that also does cognitive testing, more focused with healthcare and

00:51:39.659 --> 00:51:45.500
clinical trials. So our goal wasn't always to make them kind of fun. But funny enough,

00:51:45.500 --> 00:51:49.899
we partner with a lot of, seems like we partner with some of the same people. But specifically

00:51:49.899 --> 00:51:58.780
on the like declining cognitive abilities kind of post like 20s, mid-20s, we, yeah, I mean,

00:51:58.780 --> 00:52:04.379
generally, depending on the task, you do see some like declines from that. It's the pinnacle.

00:52:05.020 --> 00:52:09.659
But just so that in case anyone's worried, they're probably not going to be noticeable.

00:52:10.379 --> 00:52:17.179
You might be psyching yourself out a bit too much with it, that we have cognitive test performance

00:52:17.179 --> 00:52:25.419
data from like eight years to like 90. And for a lot of these tasks, there's not a big difference.

00:52:25.979 --> 00:52:32.379
Things that involve reaction time, you will see a decline. But things that rely on sort of accuracy

00:52:32.379 --> 00:52:41.179
or some sorts of, or depending on the memory paradigm, you won't have like a significant

00:52:41.179 --> 00:52:47.899
decrease, unless there is some neurodegenerative disorder or some sort of injury. But if you're

00:52:47.899 --> 00:52:54.379
generally a healthy person, you can probably still beat your 12-year-old brother. Yeah. I mean,

00:52:54.860 --> 00:53:03.179
the other thing that's important is sleep. So yeah, you need to, you know, I think there are

